{"text": "Spoiler Warning I very much enjoyed this, this really brought me back to the days of the PS1 era, nothing but pizza and Playstation for years. This game is an homage to the old school horror gems like Resident Evil and Silent Hill. It has everything, the tank controls, aesthetics, atmosphere, horror, all the way down to even the door animations after you open one. Story is you play as a woman named Emma, a intern who along with a news crew go to a seemingly abandoned house in the woods to investigate the story of the Easter Ripper Serial Killer, and once they are there, they start getting picked off one by one and you alone must make it out alive. Right off the bat, it has that nice VHS filter feel, the moving lines and blurs, everything, and if that does not fancy you, you can easily change that in the options. In true Resident Evil form, gameplay wise, you go through the house with the tank controls, finding keys and other objects to progress in the game while avoiding the killer. You have a gun and a firepoker at your disposal to scare him away for a bit before you encounter him again. You can also collect pencils and save by writing in a notepad, AKA ink ribbons and type writers. I didn't have much negativity to say besides that last and only boss. It was kind of a game ruiner at first because at any time if you get killed in the game, you of course lose and the game closes by itself, I am sorry to say, but that is just a stupid feature and does not need to happen, just let me continue from my last save, I had to do that twice from that terrible last boss. Overall, it is a solid game that does stick true to old school horror formula, that will keep you on edge. Sadly short as this game will take you around 2 hours to beat, but still worth a try.", "appid": "1064460", "steamid": "profiles/76561198117831388", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "6", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1603713600.0}
