{"text": "Well if there was a so-so vote it would fit this title perfectly. The retro nostalgia fashion is already yesterday's news, and steam is flooded with titles that try hard to hide their swallowness behind low-fi pixel art. Is this the case here? Taken as an adventure proper, with its linearity, absolute lack of challenging puzzles, and shortness, DreamBreak would be passable at best. But as a statement of cold war era's pop culture, or as a clever comment on the awkward and comic aspects of the surrounding political atmosphere, the \"game\" works surprisingly well. I have no idea whether this was the devs' deliberate intention, or just my interpretation of an otherwise naive dystopian platformer, but for me DreamBreak did the trick to a certain extent. To the game's merits is the visual beauty and the interesting soundtrack. Having said that, however, the potential for a truly exceptional title was totally missed. There are echoes of \"another world\" and even of \"saboteur\" here (anyone out there remembering the zx spectrum's masterpiece??!). But even a zx spectrum espionage puzzle posed greater challenge to mid1980s gamers.  To conclude, if you can approach DreamBreak as a visually attractive comment on our contemporary obsession with a bygone era and its bittersweet reminiscences, go for it. Otherwise, wait for a sale, sit back and enjoy a ride on soviet arcade for an hour or so.  PS for the devs: with such short timeplay please consider making the dlc part of the standard edition. It would be fair for those few, such as myself, who will invest on the title because they want indie devs to keep goingðŸ˜‰", "appid": "443570", "steamid": "profiles/76561198059030698", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "8", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1474718400.0}
