{"text": "I am happy to give the thumbs up to this game. It made me happy, then it made me angry, and still, I had great time with it. At the price that it is, and with the options that it has, it is definitely a great buy, As such, time for the good and the bad. The GOOD: 1. The PRICE: if any of you think this is a cheap cash in, you should browse the steam store and tell me how many worse games there are out there are twice or three times the price of 10â‚¬. Enough said. Dispute me, and please don't show me discounted good games from 5 years ago... 2. The SETTING: we are in post XCOM2 setting where we learned to live together with the aliens. This is actually a GOOD thing. The world must head towards globalization or standalone extinction. About time humanity (or various countries) learned that lesson. 3. The PREMISE: not everyone likes it, just like in real world nowadays, even WITH the COVID (like the COVID itself, some think we can outlive, some are more disciplined, like the premise here) rampaging around. This is in essence either a snippet, or a prequel to XCOM 3, setting the stage to what it is about to happen. I will not spoil the ending of course, but let's wait and see what the future holds.  4. The GAMEPLAY: to me, it was AWESOME. It felt snappy like a darkest dungeon in 3D would look like and the BREACH mode is so damn satisfying, and allows for so many options. That is even better, as the game progresses, you get a really good feel for your squad, knowing who can get you through a hard mission or who will not. It plays awesome and it feels awesome. 5. The GRAPHICS: for a 10â‚¬ game the graphics are a beautiful mix of high and low res stuff to make the game look amazing in combat. I am really impressed by the devs, and I want them to do it again like this. If all games for 10â‚¬ do better than their counterparts and have such good graphics and gameplay, I will buy all of them and enjoy them thoroughly. 6. The CITY: unlike XCOM, you more of a SWAT-type organization, which is worse in some regards, but way more fun in others. I loved the tactical changes on a lesser scale and in close quarters. Now I know I need to do better than bring 2 snipers and 1 cloaked character who destroy the entire battlefield.Which I totally abused in the original XCOM 1 and 2. 7. The decisions: the Expert difficulty, akin to Commander in XCOM, has always been the best for me, grinding my gears, working me up, and was way worth it. There were clutch decisions, but still, one could predict in advance if familiar with other XCOM games. THOROUGHLY enjoyable. I felt really pressed how to play, where to put my squads, whom to train, and whom to sacrifice on coverts ops. It felt good, albeit sometimes annoying. 8. MUCH LESS SAVE-SCUMMING: I decided to play without Ironman on my first expert mission, as it is an early launch and I expected trouble, as each and every XCOM game had its glitches, bugs, freezes, etc. This one has them too, but damn, people seemed to actually hit their percentages now!!! While there are whiffs, still, they do better than an usual XCOM2 game. I had whole missions on EXPERT where I was cruising and enjoying myself thoroughly without having to scream at my screen every freaking 5 seconds! 9. You will excuse me, but am I am your average, jovial, flirty, happy-go-lucky guy. As such I did NOT terribly mind the dialog, albeit it garnered a few sarcastic laughs. As such I am ok with it. Some jokes hit and some jokes miss. 10. The LORE: this game makes a some stuff cannon (including some XCOM friend or foe participants, I will not spoil much, I will just say, Director Kelly isn't a random name. Let's leave it at that. 11. UPGRADES; There are great EPIC weapons who can help your classes perform multiple roles. I had Cherub with an epic gun that allowed lightning reflexes, so he could either shield or shoot three times in a round, which is bonkers for a front liner!!! Now about if you add some armor piercing? Or turn your shotgun girl into an armor piercing 2-shot machine that joins last in the breach but acts as one of the first? The options are so much it is insane for every character. The BAD: 1. TO me it was SOME of the banter. While I enjoy jovial and light-hearted stuff something is too much on the nose. You squeezed your tender skin? Like your private parts? In an  engagement? Come on adrenaline trumps everything. So shut up with your childish behavior, Terminal. 2. FINE, I will join on the bandwagon as you cannot rename characters. Big deal. WOO-HOO-HOO. Whatever shall I do with my life afterwards. 3. Lower stakes than XCOM 1 & 2. You save Gotham city and not the world. Boo. AND NOTHING ELSE: Conclusion: For a 10â‚¬ buy, this is a 10/10, 50/50, 100/100 game for everyone who enjoys XCOM. It is fun, it has the spirit of XCOM, it has the XCOM in everything and in its core. Missions are fun and they throw a lot at you, and should be played on higher difficulties, as each and every XCOM game needs to be played. Lose or win, you will learn. This is the XCOM way. As it has always been.", "appid": "882100", "steamid": "profiles/76561198062930115", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "28", "votes_funny": "1", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1587988800.0}
