{"text": "Borderlands 2 takes place a few years after the original, and along with it, four new vault hunters including two DLC ones to go along with them. Each gives the player a diverse choice of characters, each one with varying playstyles and builds, as well as giving the game replayability. Want to dual wield guns, while being a monster of a tank? Try Salvador, the gunzerker. Want to go the whole game with just the use of melee weapons and not much gun play? There's Zer0 the assassin with blades and stealth attacks, as well as Krieg the Psycho with his buzz axe. These characters are super memorable for their quotes, various ECHO logs which can be found on the various maps in the game, and their great skills which you'll unlock and experience after leveling up. With the game having 72 levels, plus 8 extra levels called overpowered levels, you'll get to extensively play as one character for a long time, to optimize them for coop play or for playing with other max leveled people. With no limit to character slots on the PC version, you'll be playing through the game roughly six times to experience everyone, each character changing up how you play the game. But that's not even including the new game plus, where after you beat the game's story on normal mode, you'll unlock the True Vault Hunter Mode, which restarts the campaign, but on a higher difficulty with better loot and tougher enemies, as well as new variants and badass enemy ranks entirely! If that wasn't enough of a challenge, the game presents to you the agonizingly hard Ultimate Vault Hunter Mode, a difficulty even HARDER than the True Vault Hunter Mode, with even better loot, even more enemy variants, enemies constantly regenerating health, and all the enemies will always be on your level, or that of the highest level in your lobby. There's also the many DLC campaigns, each of varying lengths and difficulty, each with their own levels of entertainment, humor, side missions, story missions, and unique weapons. If you're a completionist kind of person, the game sports a challenge system, which rewards badass rank to make all your characters tougher as you complete challenges. These challenges are then able to be redone again on other characters, new and old as long as they haven't completed them yet. There's also the decent number of achievements in the game, which ALL are unlockable, and with no glitches barring them from being unlocked. So with so much to complete, you'll be playing this game for hundreds and hundreds of hours just to complete everything! This game is worth it even without DLC, just for the story, because its THAT freakin' good. However, everything good has some bad too it, as nothing is ever perfect. The game is only worth buying if you're purchasing the Handsome Collection, as that bundles gives you all the DLC for both Borderlands 2 and Borderlands: the Pre-Sequel, as well as all the extra content you get with that special edition, all at a discounted price. However, this bundle rarely goes on sale, and if so, its still relatively high in price. The last great discount of the bundle is when the bundle only costed $20, with the announcement of the soon to arrive Borderlands 3.  The game however, DOES go on sale fairly often at certain intervals of the year, so it'll never be something you can miss too often, you'll have a lot of chances to go and buy the game if you want to wait for a sale.  When playing in Coop, you can come across loot ninjas and griefers, some of the time, but not a lot. Griefers are especially annoying, as they can disrupt your gameplay, and in some cases, forcing you to leave and put your game back up. While there is a kicking option, there will be times where it may be too late to boot them, when all the damage will have had been already done. Loot ninjas are worse, as loot isn't distributed right. Quest rewards for example, give the reward item to all players in the lobby when its turnt in, as well as a choice between items in some cases. However, when farming bosses or chests, this is different. Say for example you find a Jakobs pistol, which has decent damage and accuracy. This gun only appears as one, with no copies available. Which can lead to a lot of terrible instances, such as people pressing their bound key to pick up all the loot they see, people looting someone else's item(s) if they desire it so badly and greed gets the best of them. Or people even picking up rare loot such as legendaries, before disconnecting from the game, never to come back. This not only makes the game harder, as you will have to eventually get better rarity guns on the later difficulties, but is flat out infuriating. Thankfully, those instances don't happen a lot, as the community is generally nice. And if it does happen, just kick them if you're the host. But wanna know what SHOULD happen? You going out of the way, to buy this game. Whether you play solo or coop, you'll have a hell of a blast!", "appid": "49520", "steamid": "profiles/76561198160455790", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": 0, "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1559563200.0}
