{"text": "04/08/2018  I didnâ€™t play this on release, I can only imagine just how bad it was then.  It currently feels like a steam early access Alpha.  Basically, Play Osiris New dawn, an earyl access game by a tiny indie developer that does everything this game does better.  Perhaps this is ok on console with no other titles to compete.  On PC this is a worse game than pretty much every other space builder / survival game out there.   The only good thing that can be said is that its procedurally generated but this basically means there is no real content only the same thing repeated, again and again with a different skin. The user side of the game feels like it has been coded at 4am by a student to get a minimal grade, it is all just about functional, but it is not designed for users.  The menuâ€™s are just bad, even on console they are bad and no effort has been made on PC.  Feels like using menuâ€™s early programming courses in school teach you to make.  They need to hire somebody to fix this. Every hour of play is about 20 mins of play, 20 mins of loading and traveling and 20 mins of clunky menus. When you start the game your locked into a tutorial that limits what you can do in the game.  I died of cold because I hadnâ€™t unlocked the part of the tutorial that would fix that.  I was unable to launch my ship because the tutorial wanted me to build a drive I had already built, a known issue on the forums where the answer was start the game again. Frankly a button to simply turn off the tutorial would have been more helpful. Space combat is like an old fashioned arcade minigame and seems to have no purpose apart from existing.  I decided to kill the â€œpoliceâ€ to see what would happen, after wave 5, the spawns just stop, but your unable to warp or leave the area.  As if the game never expected you to just stand there and shoot the police. It is not multiplayer, its 4 player co-op, with almost every limitation and no real benefit.  Playing with other players can also cause quite game breaking bugs, you can loose your loot if you die, you can build a base next to a one time use upgrade station another player finds then use every time you load in. The one redeeming feature is the base building has lots of tiles/shapes.  Like Osiris new dawn / subnautica it has modular habitats that lock together with tubes on foundations and free build pieces.  It actually has a few more pieces than Osiris and they all look very pretty.    Having said that, buildings are locked behind grinding salvage and only become available after you have researched a previous building on the page, so its mostly random what parts you get.  A lot of the main pieces are also locked behind â€œmissionsâ€ go here click here, repeated again and again, some simply ask you to wait an hour.  These unlock in seemingly random order (large refinery unlocked before medium refinery so medium is never used).  You also have to use a tree menu to build, Z > scroll to building > scroll to habitats > scroll to blocks > scroll to the block you want, place the blockâ€¦RESET.  5 buttons every time you build a block.  Same for colouring and textures. I really tried.  I built a 600 block base, 47 hours played, 300k on foot exploration, made 8 million trading, killed 120 ships, got max standing with Vyâ€™keen(this does nothing) Learned all the words from 2 races, Killed sentinel Walkers till they stopped spawningâ€¦. ran the main story quests for long as I could bare it and found out they were simply looping endlessly. At the moment I just canâ€™t recommend this game, it felt like an effort to play. It really needs playtesting, Player feedback, then a few solid months of Dev time to bring it out of alpha state.  Itâ€™s a shame, you can feel the potential. Play Subnautica or Osiris new dawn", "appid": "275850", "steamid": "profiles/76561197970685560", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "11", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1533384000.0}
