{"text": "FATE/Extella is a boring game, shame on you Marvelous for making this game. The story has something to do with FATE, I never read or watch the anime, so I won't speak of it in my review.  Graphic The graphic quality in this game is average at best, a bit like PS3 graphic. Eventhough graphic is not the main factor in a game (at least for me), same thing can't be said for others. Fortunately characters's animation are a okay, and their design is somewhat unique but because of the mediocre graphic, it doesn't look good. One thing that I found entertaining is each characters Noble Phantasm and Extella Maneuver, pretty catchy especially the ones with big boobies (don't judge, I am a simple man) Sound & music Music is entertaining enough, still it can't help the boring gameplay. Sound and character's voices are okay, nothing to say in this matter. Gameplay This is the core of a game, while graphic, music aren't good enough, as long as the gameplay is good, people might be able to accept it, even liking it. Sadly, this is not the case in FATE/Extella. Basically, the gameplay can be described like this: go to a stage -> kill lots of enemies to summon the aggressors (the captain in an area) -> kill aggressors -> go to another area -> kill lots of enemies to summon the aggressors -> repeat steps 1 to 4 until you get enough keys to summon the regime matrix (you use this to summon the boss of that stage) -> defeat the boss, and you're done.  Enemies has 6-7 variations, from agressor with sword, axe, stone/sling thrower, giant one, flying one, and plant (the thing that summons other aggressors), and all of them has color variations. From many stages, only one is different, the last boss stage. There is no weapons in this game, only a code cast (kind like equipment, and the only one), each code cast can be crafted using QP (the currency in this game), but in order to get the blueprint for the code cast, you need to beat certain stage in certain difficulty in certain ranks. When you've crafted it, you can equip it, each code cast has 2 or more abilities to use (max is 4).  Besides code cast, there is a thing called install skills, you can get this by defeating a servant or aggressors in any stage. Duplicate install skills will automatically fused together creating a higher level install skills, e.g.: EXP UP fused with another EXP UP will become an EXP UP+2, with max is +20. Each character has several slot skills which can be unlocked by increasing your bond with them. Bond can be increased by completing their respective side missions, all are easy.  Conclusion: FATE/Extella is clearly for a hardcore fans only, I bought this because the gameplay is similar to Dynasy Warriors series, but didn't think that it would be worse than Dynasty Warriors, at least in Dynasty Warriors you are not forced to kill hundreds of enemies just to summon the enemy's generals. If you are a hardcore fan, go for it, but I strongly advice to wait for a sale, it doesn't worth full price. If you are a DW fans, don't. Just wait for Dynasty Warriors 9 on February 2018.", "appid": "511680", "steamid": "profiles/76561198190583586", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "9", "votes_funny": "1", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1515240000.0}
