{"text": "This is one of those games that really needs a sideways thumb rating. Optimization is very poor, especially textures, which are unbearably shimmery unless you turn on TAA, which then kills performance and makes everything blurry. Tons of pop-in and bad LODs, which seem to have some kind of depth perception errors on them, so that things look like they're 2 feet away for a fraction of a second, before they snap back into the distance. It looked very nice other than that, especially some of the lighting and water effects, thanks to the Unreal Engine, but it definitely needs a lot more polish to work as a VR title. Writing... I'm sure a lot of people enjoy this kind of thing, but I honestly found it almost unbearably purple and flowery, just layer after layer of metaphor, purple prose, and trite philosophy, caked on like cheap makeup. \"Men love it when you really glob it on\" was clearly the guiding principle here. Also on the writing, despite this being ostensibly a story of love and loss, there's absolutely no characterization worth noting. None. What was Renee like? Let's see. She was female. Shy and introverted. Liked nature and hiking. That's it. What was the protagonist, Kai, like? Male and the same. There is genuinely no characterization beyond that, none whatsoever. How are we supposed to be attached to characters that have about as much personality as gingerbread men? I got the game as part of a bundle, $2.49 for 10 games. So at a hair under 25 cents, I don't feel ripped off in the slightest. But it only had 1 hour of total gameplay, and did NOT leave me wanting any more. I really cannot recommend buying this at full price, so it has to get a thumbs down rating from me, lacking a \"neutral vote\" or \"wait until it's on sale for under $1\" option.", "appid": "720290", "steamid": "profiles/76561197976576606", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "5", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1525867200.0}
