{"text": "the basic idea seemed nice at first view. Manage your ship, fly around space anbd destroy other ships, customize your weapons and systems at stations, hire crew to boost stats. Classic rpg. Sadly, it feels like it was designed for you to be level 50 on the first mission. You dont take much damage but it takes about 5 minutes to destroy 1 ship and within the first 15 minutes of the game you encounter 7 ennemy ships.... There is hours of useless travel between missions, ship's hp vs weapons is really unbalanced, the voice acting is terrible and most of time cut out the last sentence. Im glad i got it for free because i would definitely not have paid for that. Unless you love spending alot of time holding a mouse click or holding the forward thrust without doing anything for 5 minutes, dont buy this. (on a side note, i think companies selling a game 50$ for a few months then giving it away for free are really unfair to all their customers whom paid for it. If i had paid 50$ for it and discover that everyone can get it permanently for free now, i would be really mad at the company and never buy any of their products anymore.)", "appid": "236150", "steamid": "profiles/76561198041779541", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "1", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1495627200.0}
{"text": "This game reminds me of a comment Jonathen Blow made about AAA games these days evoking feeling of bad action movies. I said it, and I feel that's just what Tomb Raider is. At the beginning of the game I was hooked into the setting. The graphics were beautiful, the controls responsive the sound design well done... it had all the potential in the world. This is still a game I'd personally recommend as something to play to other people, but I'd wait for a bargain bin price personally. For me what began as fun, finding all the little collectibles and doing side hunt after side hunt, quickly spiraled into okay I just wanna finish this game. The story was completely uninteresting to me. I could partially blame this on playing Specs Ops: The Line before this. I want to care about characters like that. I cared about no one in Tomb Raider. That and some of the trials and tribulations Lara initially goes through emotionally speaking, I could be speaking out of cynicism here, but I felt they were just there to show her feminism. This saddens me. I hate saying something like that. I also think it's poor of developer to make a choice that, \"this is how a female would act.\" This could be my cynicism again. I just can't help but feel the writing direction was well â™¥â™¥â™¥â™¥. The character development was â™¥â™¥â™¥â™¥. Calling action sequence, chase sequence, or exploration sequence before they were happening just show how un-immersed I was. I was watching the game more than actively engaging with it. It was a â™¥â™¥â™¥â™¥â™¥â™¥ B action movie with a pedigree. Even then Lara never felt like she made a place. You could have swapped out with any \"dude bro\" and the game wouldn't have been any different. When you can swap out your main character I'd think that's a clue that she's under developed. On top of all of my personal opinion and cynicism lies the end of the game. Terribly anti-climactic and un-impactful like the game as a whole itself.", "appid": "203160", "steamid": "profiles/76561198025324740", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "11", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1385380800.0}
