{"text": "Long story short: It's like a popular horror movie arch-villain that comes up to you and tries to steal your lunch money, but you stand up to it, unfazed. Then the villain walks away crying. Lost In Vivo is a first person survival horror game set in a deep, dark sewer. Navigate an underground labyrinth, fight monsters and solve puzzles. There is no jump button so there's no pitfall platforming involved. One rainy afternoon while walking your dog, the latter will get sucked into a water drain down the sewers. Without hesitation, you find the nearest manhole and chase after him. Was it a good idea? Probably not, but your resolve is unyielding. Very quickly, things start to go wrong and you can't go back the way you came... Clearly inspired by Silent Hill and SCP creepy pastas, Lost In Vivo has an other-wordly vibe to it where anything goes. Rocking with the Unity Game engine, this game uses a pixelated approach for its textures. It's not spectacular but it's been widely accepted by survival horror veterans that using low-res texture can sometimes enhance the experience. Also, they've done a good job with the lightning. The overall map design is ok. A bit repetitive in some areas, but what can you do, it's a man-made sewer, we like to copy and paste things in real life too. The sound department is where this game really shines. Using carefully placed 3D sounds, the game won't lack some unsettling moments. Also, the soundtrack in general is really good, following the vibe of Silent Hill's well-known palette of sonic pandemonium. On the surface, just like real life, this is a decent, good game, but if you stare into the nearest sewer manhole, you're going to see the crusty, stinky side of your street. To kick things off, the Store page description claims this is a game about Claustrophobia or fear of small spaces/rooms. Half-way through the game, you'll soon realise this is entirely about something else. I won't get into it much if the game interests you, but it's crystal-clear the description is misleading. Like the 2nd paragraph claims; anything goes... Next, we have gameplay. There's a lack enemies in most places, making this game feel borderline-walking-simulator. Then, you have poor weapon balance. Knife has highest DPS than Pistol, but the Pistol does more damage than Shotgun. Then there's Regenerating Health with no Health pickup. And finally, a useless inventory menu because all gun equipping and reloading, as well as using Key Items is done outside of the menu. What you have here are gameplay mechanics that aren't really engaging. Third, the endings. There are 4 different endings so far with 2 of them being a bit cryptic because there's no in-game clue on how to get them. But that's not the real problem here. It's the missed opportunities to properly separate these endings based on your choices throughout the game.  There's at least 4 instances I can think of that could have been used more wisely but in the end, served no purpose. And there's no Stats screen at the end... Finally, some technical aspects. If you make the mistake of rebinding your keys in the Unity launcher, you'll disable controller support and there's no direct way to reset to default. The game's volume may or may not work properly. If another object's interacting prompt hovers on your screen before opening a door, you may softlock the game. Menus cannot be navigated with mouse, only WASD. No \"Always Run\" toggle. In the end, this game is what happens when you try to write a love letter to the genre while struggling to understand what the genre was about in the first place. Like I mentioned in one of my previous survival horror review, finding a good balance between gameplay and story is key to making a great survival horror game. Turns out this game doesn't deliver on neither front. There are scary and unsettling moments, but the general meaningful impact isn't really felt. I recommend this game for Beginner-tier survival horror fans who don't want to think too much. It's very easy. I cannot recommend this game for Veteran-tier survival horror fans as most of us have seen a lot better elsewhere... I rate this a solid 5/10, loose 6/10. I would vote Neutral if there was one.", "appid": "963710", "steamid": "profiles/76561197989933933", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "26", "votes_funny": "4", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1573473600.0}
